# Higher Order Derivatives

If $f$ is a function of two variables, then so are its partial derivatives, the so called **second partial derivatives**.
If $z = f(x, y)$ we use the following notation:

$$\begin{align*}
(f_x)_x &= f_{xx} = f_{11} = \pleibniz{x}\left(\pleibniz[f]{x}\right) = \pleibniz[^2f]{x^2} = \pleibniz[^2z]{x^2}                 \\
(f_x)_y &= f_{xy} = f_{12} = \pleibniz{y}\left(\pleibniz[f]{x}\right) = \pleibniz[^2f]{y\partial x} = \pleibniz[^2z]{y\partial x} \\
(f_y)_x &= f_{yx} = f_{21} = \pleibniz{x}\left(\pleibniz[f]{y}\right) = \pleibniz[^2f]{x\partial y} = \pleibniz[^2z]{x\partial y} \\
(f_y)_y &= f_{yy} = f_{22} = \pleibniz{y}\left(\pleibniz[f]{y}\right) = \pleibniz[^2f]{y^2} = \pleibniz[^2z]{y^2}
\end{align*}$$

This notation can be generalized in the obvious way.

